VALUES
(43, 2, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'made a scourge of small cords', 16, 45, 'greek', 'Scourge Significance', 'The Greek word used here for ''scourge'' is μαστίγιον (mastigion, G3149) - a whip or rod. This term emphasizes the physicality of Jesus'' actions in the temple, symbolizing authority and judgment. The use of a scourge is not merely about expelling the merchants but also signifies a deeper call to reverence for sacred spaces.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3149", "description": "Strong''s definition of the Greek term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'drove them all out of the temple', 50, 82, 'theology', 'Temple Cleansing', 'This passage illustrates Jesus'' role as a reformer, emphasizing the sanctity of the temple. Many scholars believe that this act signifies not just a physical cleansing but a prophetic declaration against corruption in worship. It highlights the importance of purity in our approach to God and the seriousness with which we treat sacred spaces.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on the significance of Jesus'' actions in the temple."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'overthrew the tables', 153, 173, 'connection', 'Symbolic Actions', 'This act recalls Old Testament themes of judgment and restoration, notably seen in Jeremiah 7:11, where God expresses disdain for false worship in the temple. This connection matters because it frames Jesus'' actions within a prophetic context, asserting His authority as the Messiah who restores true worship.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Jeremiah 7:11", "description": "Reference to God''s condemnation of false worship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'Take these things hence; make not my Father''s house an house of merchandise.', 36, 112, 'connection', 'Temple Purity Theme', 'This command echoes the sentiments found in Jeremiah 7:11, where the Lord rebukes Israel for turning the temple into a den of robbers. Both passages highlight God''s desire for His house to be a place of worship rather than commercial activity. Understanding this connection deepens our appreciation of Jesus'' righteous anger and His commitment to preserving the sanctity of the temple.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Jeremiah 7:11", "description": "God''s rebuke of the misuse of the temple."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'my Father''s house', 70, 87, 'greek', 'Father''s House in Greek', 'οἶκος (oikos, G3624) - house, household. This term signifies not just a physical building, but also a familial and communal space. By referring to the temple as ''my Father''s house,'' Jesus emphasizes the intimate relationship between God and His people, stressing that worship is fundamentally relational rather than transactional.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3624", "description": "Greek word for house or household."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'make not my Father''s house an house of merchandise.', 61, 112, 'theology', 'Worship vs. Commercialism', 'Many scholars believe this passage critiques the commercialization of faith. It suggests that worship should be about reverence and authenticity, not profit. The underlying theology stresses that God desires pure worship that honors His holiness, as seen in Psalm 29:2, which calls for worship in the beauty of holiness. This challenges believers to reflect on the motivations behind their acts of worship.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 29:2", "description": "Call to worship in holiness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'Take these things hence;', 36, 60, 'question', 'Personal Application', 'What does it mean for you to ''take these things hence'' in your own life? Are there areas where commercialism or distractions have entered your worship, and how can you realign your focus on reverence for God''s presence?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'The zeal of thine house', 50, 73, 'connection', 'Old Testament Reference', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 69:9, which states, ''For zeal for your house consumes me, and the reproaches of those who reproach you have fallen on me.'' This connection underscores the deep passion Jesus has for the sanctity of worship and the temple, illustrating His righteous anger towards corruption within sacred spaces.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 69:9", "description": "A psalm attributing zeal for God''s house to suffering and passion."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'hath eaten me up', 74, 90, 'greek', 'Significant Greek Term', 'ἐσθίω (esthio, G2068) - to eat, consume. This term implies a deep, all-consuming passion that is almost devouring in nature. It suggests that Jesus'' commitment to God''s house is not just a surface-level concern but an all-encompassing drive that shapes His identity and actions.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2068", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term meaning ''to eat'' or ''to consume.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'The zeal of thine house', 50, 73, 'theology', 'Righteous Zeal for God', 'This passage suggests that zeal for God''s house is a fundamental aspect of faith. Many scholars believe that Jesus'' actions here reflect the idea that worship and devotion should be prioritized over commercial interests, emphasizing that the church''s purpose is for spiritual nourishment rather than material gain.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "A well-known commentary that discusses the significance of zeal in worship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'his disciples remembered', 4, 28, 'question', 'Reflection on Memory', 'What does it mean for us to remember the zeal of Jesus when we approach worship today? How can we ensure that our places of worship reflect this same commitment to honoring God rather than becoming mere venues for commerce or entertainment?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'What sign shewest thou unto us,', 42, 73, 'connection', 'Signs in John', 'This inquiry into signs parallels other instances in John where the Jewish leaders demand proof of Jesus'' authority, such as in John 6:30, where they ask for a sign like manna from heaven. These requests reveal a persistent skepticism about Jesus'' identity and mission. Understanding this context helps readers grasp the significance of Jesus'' subsequent declaration about the temple.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 6:30", "description": "Another instance of the Jews demanding a sign from Jesus."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'What sign shewest thou unto us,', 42, 73, 'theology', 'Authority and Signs', 'This verse raises theological questions about the nature of authority and the signs that accompany it. Many scholars believe that signs serve as divine validation of Jesus'' mission, indicating that faith should not solely rest on empirical evidence but also on spiritual insight. This reflects a broader Christian understanding of faith as belief in the unseen, as emphasized in Hebrews 11:1.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 11:1", "description": "Definition of faith as belief in what is not seen."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'What sign shewest thou unto us,', 42, 73, 'question', 'Seeking Signs', 'In what ways do we, like the Jews, seek signs to validate our faith? How might this reflect a deeper struggle to trust in Jesus'' authority and presence in our lives today? Reflecting on this question can lead to a better understanding of our own faith journey and the importance of believing without seeing.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up.', 35, 93, 'connection', 'Foreshadowing Resurrection', 'This phrase connects with Matthew 27:40, where Jesus'' words about the temple are recalled during His crucifixion. The Jews challenge Him, highlighting their misunderstanding of His reference to His body as the temple. This connection emphasizes the prophetic nature of Jesus'' statement, illustrating that His death and resurrection were foreseen and central to His mission.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 27:40", "description": "Reference to Jesus'' words about the temple during His crucifixion."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Destroy this temple', 35, 54, 'greek', 'Greek Term for Temple', 'ναός (naos, G3485) - temple, specifically referring to the inner sanctuary. This distinction matters because it highlights that Jesus is not only speaking of the physical building but rather the sacredness of His body as the dwelling place of God. The term indicates a deeper theological implication regarding the incarnation and the presence of God among humanity.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3485", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'in three days I will raise it up.', 60, 93, 'theology', 'Sign of the Resurrection', 'This statement suggests that Jesus'' resurrection is central to Christian faith, as expressed in 1 Corinthians 15:14. Many scholars believe that the resurrection not only validates Jesus'' divine authority but also signifies the promise of eternal life for believers. Understanding this context is crucial for grasping the full scope of salvation and Christ''s victory over death.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Corinthians 15:14", "description": "Paul''s teaching on the importance of the resurrection."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'I will raise it up.', 74, 93, 'question', 'Understanding Resurrection Power', 'What does it mean for Jesus to ''raise it up'' in three days? How does this promise impact your understanding of His power over life and death? Reflecting on this can deepen your appreciation for the resurrection as not just a historical event but a present reality that influences our daily lives and hope.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Forty and six years was this temple in building, and wilt thou rear it up in three days?', 20, 108, 'connection', 'Temple Significance', 'The reference to the temple''s construction period connects to other biblical accounts of the temple''s importance. For instance, 1 Kings 6:37-38 details Solomon''s temple construction over seven years, emphasizing the significance of the temple as a dwelling place for God. This context highlights the Jews'' disbelief in Jesus'' claim, as they see the temple as a monumental physical structure rather than understanding it as a foreshadowing of Christ''s resurrection.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Kings 6:37-38", "description": "Details the construction of Solomon''s temple."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 26:61", "description": "Refers to Jesus'' claim about destroying the temple."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Forty and six years was this temple in building', 20, 67, 'greek', 'Temple (ναός)', 'ναός (naos, G3485) - temple, sanctuary. This term refers specifically to the inner sanctuary of the temple, where God''s presence dwelled. The Jews'' focus on the physical structure contrasts with Jesus'' declaration about His body as the true temple, revealing a deeper spiritual truth about His identity and mission.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3485", "description": "Strong''s number for the word ''temple''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'wilt thou rear it up in three days?', 73, 108, 'theology', 'Resurrection Foretelling', 'This passage suggests that Jesus'' reference to raising the temple in three days is a profound foreshadowing of His resurrection. Many scholars believe this highlights the centrality of the resurrection in Christian faith, asserting that Jesus'' victory over death is the ultimate sign of His divine authority. The resurrection transforms the understanding of sacred space, moving it from a physical location to the person of Christ.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "John 2:21-22", "description": "Commentary on Jesus'' reference to His body as the temple."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Forty and six years was this temple in building', 20, 67, 'question', 'Understanding Historical Context', 'What does the lengthy construction of the temple reveal about the significance of religious spaces in our lives today? How does this historical context enhance our understanding of Jesus'' claim about His own body as the temple?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'temple of his body', 20, 38, 'connection', 'Resurrection Theme', 'This phrase connects to 1 Corinthians 6:19, where Paul teaches that our bodies are temples of the Holy Spirit. Both verses emphasize the sanctity of the body in relation to God''s presence, highlighting a transformative understanding of what it means to be a temple. This connection illustrates how Jesus'' resurrection not only signifies His divine authority but also sets the stage for believers to recognize their own bodies as sacred.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Corinthians 6:19", "description": "Paul''s teaching on the body as a temple"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'temple of his body', 20, 38, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Temple''', 'ναός (naos, G3485) - temple, sanctuary. This term specifically refers to the inner sanctuary of a temple, where the divine presence dwells. In this context, it underscores the significance of Jesus'' body as not just a physical form, but as the very place of God''s presence and glory, foreshadowing His resurrection.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3485", "description": "Strong''s Greek number for ''temple''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'But he spake of the temple of his body.', 0, 39, 'theology', 'Christ as the True Temple', 'This passage suggests that Jesus redefines the concept of the temple. Traditionally, the temple was a physical location for worship, but Jesus presents His body as the ultimate dwelling place of God. This idea aligns with Hebrews 10:19-20, where the author explains that through Jesus'' sacrifice, believers can enter the holy presence of God, indicating a new covenant relationship.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 10:19-20", "description": "Believers'' access to God through Christ"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'But he spake of the temple of his body.', 0, 39, 'question', 'Personal Reflection on Christ', 'What does it mean for you personally to understand Jesus'' body as the temple? How does recognizing this impact your view of His sacrifice and your relationship with Him today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'he was risen from the dead', 15, 41, 'greek', 'Resurrection Significance', 'ἐγείρω (egeirō, G1453) - to raise up, awaken. This term emphasizes the active role of God in the resurrection of Christ. It signifies not only a physical rising but also a spiritual awakening for believers. The resurrection is foundational to Christian faith, affirming Jesus as the Son of God and providing hope of eternal life.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1453", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term used"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'they believed the scripture', 105, 132, 'connection', 'Fulfillment of Prophecy', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 16:10, where it is prophesied that God''s Holy One will not see decay. The disciples'' belief in the scripture after witnessing the resurrection highlights the fulfillment of Old Testament prophecies, showcasing the continuity of God''s plan through Jesus.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 16:10", "description": "Prophecy of the resurrection"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'remembered that he had said this unto them', 57, 99, 'theology', 'Role of Memory in Faith', 'This passage suggests that the act of remembering is crucial in the process of faith formation. Many scholars believe that the recall of Jesus'' words serves as a divine confirmation of His identity and mission, reinforcing the importance of scripture and Jesus'' teachings in the life of believers.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "John 2:22", "description": "Insight on the role of memory in faith"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'believed the scripture', 110, 132, 'question', 'Understanding Belief', 'What does it mean to believe the scripture in light of the resurrection? How does this belief impact your understanding of God''s promises and your daily life? Reflect on the transformative power that belief in God''s word can have in your faith journey.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Now when he was in Jerusalem at the passover, in the feast day, many believed in his name, when they saw the miracles which he did.', 0, 131, 'connection', 'Passover Significance', 'The mention of Passover in this verse connects to Exodus 12:14, where the Passover is established as a festival commemorating Israel''s deliverance from Egypt. This connection emphasizes the theme of deliverance, linking Jesus'' miracles to the greater narrative of salvation. Additionally, John 3:2 reflects how Nicodemus acknowledges Jesus as a teacher sent from God due to the signs he performs, highlighting the importance of miracles in affirming Jesus'' divine authority.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 12:14", "description": "Establishes the Passover festival''s significance in Israel''s history."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 3:2", "description": "Nicodemus recognizes Jesus'' authority through his miracles."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'many believed in his name', 64, 89, 'theology', 'Belief in Jesus'' Authority', 'This phrase suggests a foundational Christian doctrine regarding faith in Jesus as the Messiah. Many scholars believe this reflects the Johannine theme of belief as a response to signs and miracles. The act of believing in Jesus'' name signifies trust in his character and authority, which is central to the Gospel''s message of salvation. Belief is not merely intellectual assent but entails a relational trust in who Jesus is and what he represents.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "The Gospel According to John by D.A. Carson", "description": "Discusses the theological implications of belief in Jesus."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'when they saw the miracles which he did.', 91, 131, 'question', 'Miracles and Faith', 'How do the miracles of Jesus challenge your understanding of faith? In what ways do you see God''s work in your life that prompts belief? Reflecting on this question can deepen your appreciation for the signs that testify to Jesus'' identity and mission.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'in the feast day', 46, 62, 'greek', 'Feast Day Importance', 'ἑορτή (heortē, G1859) - feast, festival. This term denotes a significant religious celebration, emphasizing the communal aspect of faith and worship during pivotal moments in Jewish life. Understanding this context enhances our grasp of the setting in which Jesus performed his miracles, highlighting the intersection of personal faith with communal identity.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1859", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term for feast."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'But Jesus did not commit himself unto them,', 0, 43, 'connection', 'Jesus'' Discernment', 'This verse echoes John 6:64, where Jesus acknowledges that some among His followers do not believe. The connection highlights Jesus'' understanding of human nature and faith, emphasizing His selective commitment based on true belief rather than superficial attraction to miracles. It points to His divine wisdom in discerning genuine faith.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 6:64", "description": "Jesus knows who will truly believe in Him."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'because he knew all men,', 44, 68, 'greek', 'Knowledge of Humanity', 'ἔγνω (egnō, G1097) - to know, to understand, to recognize. This term indicates a deep, experiential knowledge that goes beyond mere awareness. It suggests that Jesus fully comprehends the intentions and hearts of individuals, which informs His interactions and decisions regarding whom to trust and how to engage.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1097", "description": "Greek word for ''knew'' emphasizing deep understanding."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'But Jesus did not commit himself unto them,', 0, 43, 'theology', 'The Nature of True Faith', 'This passage suggests that true faith is not merely a reaction to miracles or signs. Many scholars believe that Jesus'' reluctance to commit to those who believed superficially illustrates a theological principle: genuine faith requires a deeper relationship built on trust and understanding, rather than transient awe or curiosity.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "The Gospel of John by D.A. Carson", "description": "Discusses the nature of faith and the relationship with Jesus."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'because he knew all men,', 44, 68, 'question', 'Understanding Jesus'' Insight', 'What does it mean for Jesus to ''know all men''? How does this understanding of His omniscience affect your perception of His interactions with people? Consider how His knowledge of your heart influences your relationship with Him.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'needed not that any should testify of man', 4, 45, 'connection', 'Self-Knowledge of Christ', 'This phrase connects with 1 Samuel 16:7, where the Lord tells Samuel that He looks at the heart, not outward appearances. Just as God knows the hearts of men, Jesus, as the Son of God, possesses complete understanding of human nature. This emphasizes His divine insight and authority, affirming that believers can trust in His judgment over human testimony.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 16:7", "description": "The Lord''s perspective on human nature."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'for he knew what was in man', 47, 74, 'theology', 'Christ''s Omniscience', 'This passage suggests that Jesus'' knowledge extends beyond mere facts; it encompasses the thoughts and intentions of the human heart. According to the doctrine of omniscience, which is widely accepted in Christian theology, God''s knowledge is perfect and complete. This characteristic of Christ reassures believers that He understands their struggles and motivations, providing a profound comfort in their relationship with Him.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "A reflection on Christ''s divine knowledge."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'that any should testify of man', 15, 45, 'question', 'Testimony''s Value', 'What does it mean to rely on human testimony when Jesus, who knows our hearts, does not need it? How does this understanding influence your view of the credibility of human opinions versus divine insight?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'for he knew what was in man', 47, 74, 'greek', 'Understanding ''knew''', 'γινώσκω (ginosko, G1097) - to know, understand, perceive. This term implies a deep, relational knowledge rather than mere factual awareness. It reflects Christ''s intimate understanding of human nature, which is foundational for His ministry and interactions with people.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1097", "description": "Strong''s number for ''knew''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'There was a man of the Pharisees, named Nicodemus, a ruler of the Jews:', 0, 71, 'connection', 'Pharisees in Context', 'The mention of Nicodemus as a Pharisee is significant when considering Luke 18:10-14, where Jesus contrasts the self-righteousness of a Pharisee with the humility of a tax collector. This highlights the tension between societal religious leaders and the new teachings of Jesus. Understanding Nicodemus''s background enriches the narrative of his seeking Jesus, showing he is a learned man grappling with deeper truths.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 18:10-14", "description": "Jesus'' parable contrasting a Pharisee and a tax collector"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'There was a man of the Pharisees, named Nicodemus, a ruler of the Jews:', 0, 71, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Pharisees''', 'Φαρισαῖος (Pharisaíos, G5330) - Pharisee, a member of a Jewish sect known for strict observance of the Law and oral traditions. This term reflects the religious and sociopolitical dynamics of the time, indicating that Nicodemus, despite his high status, is drawn to Jesus for answers beyond traditional interpretations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5330", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term ''Pharisee''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'a ruler of the Jews:', 51, 71, 'theology', 'Role of Rulers', 'This phrase underscores the authority Nicodemus holds within the Jewish community, suggesting that even those in power are seeking spiritual truth. Many scholars believe that this reflects the broader theme in John''s Gospel, where Jesus engages with both the learned and the marginalized, indicating that the gospel is for all, regardless of social standings.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "John 3:1-21", "description": "Commentary on the significance of Nicodemus'' inquiry"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'There was a man of the Pharisees, named Nicodemus, a ruler of the Jews:', 0, 71, 'question', 'Seeking Truth', 'What does it mean for someone of Nicodemus''s stature to come to Jesus at night? How does this reflect our own willingness to seek truth in uncomfortable or uncertain circumstances?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'came to Jesus by night', 9, 31, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Night', 'The phrase ''by night'' can symbolize spiritual darkness or ignorance. Many scholars believe Nicodemus''s decision to approach Jesus at night reflects his fear of the Pharisees and his struggle with faith. This choice sets a tone of seeking truth amidst uncertainty, highlighting the transformative journey from darkness to light that is central to John''s Gospel.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Rabbi, we know that thou art a teacher come from God', 52, 104, 'connection', 'Recognition of Authority', 'This acknowledgment of Jesus as a teacher from God parallels John 7:46, where officers of the temple marvel at Jesus''s teaching. This connection emphasizes how Jesus''s authority was recognized by both the learned and the common people, challenging the established religious norms.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 7:46", "description": "Officers acknowledge Jesus''s unique teaching"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'for no man can do these miracles that thou doest, except God be with him', 106, 178, 'greek', 'Miracles and Divine Presence', 'ἔργα (erga, G2041) - works, deeds, miracles. Nicodemus''s reference to Jesus''s miracles underscores the divine authority behind them, suggesting that these acts are evidence of God''s presence. This term is significant in understanding the nature of Jesus''s ministry as one empowered by the Father, reinforcing the idea that faith is often awakened through witnessing God''s works.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2041", "description": "Greek word for works or miracles"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
